What do Qualitative Analysts do?

Qualitative analysis is a matter of keeping track of:

  • What you are doing:
    • Documenting the research process
    • Documenting the participants and information sources
    • Transcribing and editing your transcription
    • Archiving the raw data

What do Qualitative Analysts do?

Qualitative analysis is a matter of keeping track of:

  • What you are thinking, hearing, seeing, and feeling:
    • Field notes log
    • Analytic memos
    • Research diary

What do Qualitative Analysts do?

Qualitative analysis is a matter of keeping track of:

  • What you are finding:
    • Getting an overall sense of the data
    • Coding the data more closely
    • Expanding and merging codes (e.g.Â topics and themes)
    • Writing analytic memos about findings and interpretations
    • Identifying relationships in your data
    • Monitoring shifts in your “positionality”
    • Assessing your dataâs relationships to external contexts

How do you keep track?

DOCUMENT EVERYTHING

  • Keep a clean copy of the original research design/proposal and note any changes made from that plan.
  • Comment on methods that worked and those that did not.
  • Keep blank copies of all interview protocols, discussion outlines, questionnaires, etc.
  • Keep a tentative and actual time line and budget.
  • Document all your methods and instruments:
    • How did you find your participants?
    • How did you get permission to interview them?
    • What kind of guarantees of confidentiality or anonymity did you provide?
    • How did you get access to archival materials?

Marking Up the Text

  • Read for the overall plot or story told by the participant
    • Write this out after reading the entire text on a separate piece of paper
  • Read for your own response to the story
    • Mark up the text in blue pen in the left margin
  • Read to understand how the participant experiences, feels, and speaks about themselves
    • Mark up the text in red pen in the right margin
  • Memo your thoughts about particular participants before reading across texts
    • Write this out as your are reading, on a separate piece of paper.
Adapted from Doucet and Mauthner, 1998.

Qualitative Coding

  • Goal: to make sense of your mass of data through recognition of patterns and themes within and across texts.
    • To describe, interpret themes, or theorize on how patterns fit together
  • An iterative process â what you find can influence what you look for next and how you might reinterpret what you already found!

Coding Tips:

  • Name, donât summarize.
  • Name fully (e.g., statements can have more than one code).
  • Use consistent coding scheme (tracked in a “code book”).

How are themes linked?

  • Hierarchical: X is a kind of Y
  • Sequence: X is a step or stage in Y
  • Attribution/Nested: X is a characteristic of Y
  • Cause and Effect: X is a result of Y
  • Rationale: X is a reason for doing Y

Computer-Assisted Qualitative Data Analysis Software (CAQDAS)

  • Text Retrievers (automatic collection)
  • Text-base Managers (sorting/editing)
  • Code-and-Retrieve Programs (extract/juxtapose/associate)
  • Code-Based Theory Builders (trees/models/thematic organization)
  • Conceptual Network Builders (conceptual graphics)
“You Think, They Do”

Questions to Ask of CAQDAS:

  • Can more than one code be attached to a text segment? Can text segments overlap? Is it easy to change, delete, add individual codes?
  • Can you search for multiple codes or particular code sequences?
  • Can you search selectively, only through certain texts?
  • How easy is it to import, create, save, retrieve files?
  • How are memos handled?
  • How easy is it to learn?
  • Will it run on my computer? Is there technical support available?
  • Where is it available? How much does it cost?
  • Will it perform all the functions I need?

NVivo 12

  • Originally released as NUD*IST (1981!): “Non-numerical Unstructured Data Indexing, Searching and Theorizing”.
  • Name is a reference to “In Vivo” data (vs.Â “In Vitro”).
  • Developed by Lyn and Tom Richards, who formed QSR International.
  • Commonly used program; available on Windows and Mac OS X.

Version 12 is available through SFU:

  • http://www.lib.sfu.ca/about/branches-depts/rc/research/software/nvivo
  • https://www.lib.sfu.ca/about/branches-depts/rc/software-data-dh/software/nvivo/getting-started
  • https://www.lib.sfu.ca/about/branches-depts/rc/software-data-dh/software/nvivo/download/instructions

The 5 Steps:

  1. Gather the Ingredients: Import all reference sources to NVivo and create memos.
  2. Code the References: Create nodes, coding strips.
  3. Create cases to classify and store descriptive information: Add attributes.
  4. Run queries and analyze coded data.
  5. Present findings and prepare report.

Some important notes:

  • Data represents the actual files you are importing into your project
    • Often useful to group by source
    • Can apply “classifications” to incorporate meta-data
  • Cases represent units of observation: can be people, places, organizations, events or other entities! Cases have:
    • a classification (e.g., Person, Organization, Place); and,
    • one or more attributes (e.g., age, gender, location), which are stored in “Case Classifications” or a spreadsheet.
  • The Query Ribbon hides some very useful tools, such as the ability to run: text searches, word frequencies, coding searches, matrix coding searches, cross-tabulations, and coding comparisons!
